"id": 585, "session_id": "20260425_082424_dec2c3ed", "role": "tool", "content": "{\"content\": \"     1|# Hermes Agent Orange Book — Complete Guide Summary\\n     2|\\n     3|> Source: \\\"Hermes Agent: The Complete Guide\\\" (橙皮书 / Orange Book)\\n     4|> Author: HuaShu (花叔 / AI进化论-花生), Bilibili + WeChat\\n     5|> Version: v260408, April 2026 | Based on Hermes Agent v0.7.0\\n     6|> GitHub: github.com/alchaincyf/hermes-agent-orange-book\\n     7|> Local PDF: raw/hermes-orange-book.pdf (placeholder) | raw/papers/hermes-orange-book-en.pdf (full 77pp)\\n     8|> All Orange Books: huasheng.ai\\n     9|> License: For learning purposes only — refer to official docs for latest\\n    10|\\n    11|---\\n    12|\\n    13|## Overview\\n    14|\\n    15|Hermes Agent (by Nous Research) is the first production implementation of Harness Engineering\\n    16|— a methodology coined by Mitchell Hashimoto (Terraform creator) where you systematically build\\n    17|scaffolding around an AI model to control its behavior. Released February 2026, it hit 27,000+\\n    18|GitHub stars in two months. MIT license, fully open source.\\n    19|\\n    20|The Orange Book is a 17-chapter, 5-part guide structured as follows:\\n    21|\\n    22|  Part 1 (§01-02): Concepts\\n    23|  Part 2 (§03-06): Core Mechanisms\\n    24|  Part 3 (§07-11): Hands-On Setup\\n    25|  Part 4 (§12-15): Real-World Scenarios\\n    26|  Part 5 (§16-17): Deep Thinking\\n    27|\\n    28|---\\n    29|\\n    30|## Part 1: Concepts\\n    31|\\n    32|### §01 — Not Another Agent: From Harness to Hermes\\n    33|\\n    34|Harness Engineering background: In early 2026, the LangChain team demonstrated that adjusting\\n    35|the \\\"harness\\\" around the same model (GPT-5.2-Codex) caused benchmark scores to jump from\\n    36|52.8% to 66.5% — from Top 30 to Top 5 — without changing a single line of model code.\\n    37|\\n    38|Five Harness Components and how Hermes maps them:\\n    39|\\n    40|  Harness Component   | Manual Way                        | Hermes Built-in\\n    41|  --------------------|-----------------------------------|------------------------------------------\\n    42|  Instruction Layer   | Hand-write CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md  | Skill system (auto-created + self-improving)\\n    43|  Constraint Layer    | Configure hooks / linter / CI     | Tool permissions + sandbox + toolset on-demand\\n    44|  Feedback Layer      | Manual review / evaluator Agent   | Self-improving Learning Loop (auto-retrospective)\\n    45|  Memory Layer        | Manually maintain knowledge base  | Three-layer memory + Honcho user modeling\\n    46|  Orchestration Layer | Build your own multi-Agent pipeline | Sub-Agent delegation + cron scheduling\\n    47|\\n    48|Key differentiator from OpenClaw: OpenClaw gives you configuration-as-behavior (you write\\n    49|SOUL.md). Hermes has all five dimensions built in and they run automatically. Claude Code\\n    50|requires you to build the harness manually. Hermes builds its own harness while it runs.\\n    51|\\n    52|### §02 — Hermes Agent at a Glance: 60 Seconds\\n    53|\\n    54|Architecture in one line:\\n    55|  Learning Loop → Three-Layer Memory → Skill System → 40+ Tools → Multi-Platform Gateway\\n    56|\\n    57|Key numbers (v0.7.0, April 3, 2026):\\n    58|\\n    59|  Metric                 | Data\\n    60|  -----------------------|------------------------------------------\\n    61|  GitHub stars           | 27,000+ (two months after release)\\n    62|  Built-in tools         | 40+\\n    63|  Supported platforms    | 14\\n    64|  MCP integrations       | 6,000+ apps\\n    65|  Sub-Agent concurrency  | Up to 3\\n    66|  Minimum deployment     | $5/month VPS\\n    67|  Memory usage           | <500MB (without local LLM)\\n    68|  License                | MIT (fully open source)\\n    69|\\n    70|Cost comparison: Claude Code Pro is $20/month, Max is $200/month. Hermes on $5 VPS + API\\n    71|costs under $10/month for most use cases.\\n    72|\\n    73|---\\n    74|\\n    75|## Part 2: Core Mechanisms\\n    76|\\n    77|### §03 — The Learning Loop: Self-Harnessing Agent\\n    78|\\n    79|Five steps wired into a closed loop — the flywheel that makes Hermes improve over time:\\n    80|\\n    81|  Curate Memory → Create Skill → Skill Self-Improvement → FTS5 Recall → User Modeling\\n    82|\\n    83|Step 1: Memory Curation\\n    84|  After each conversation Hermes actively decides what to keep — not passive storage.\\n    85|  Works like writing a diary: looks back at the exchange, decides what was notable, writes\\n    86|  it to SQLite with FTS5 indexing. A periodic nudge mechanism reminds the agent to review\\n    87|  recent interactions (like a journaling app notification). Not a video tape — a notebook.\\n    88|\\n    89|Step 2: Autonomous Skill Creation\\n    90|  When Hermes finishes a complex task, it asks: \\\"will this solution be useful again?\\\"\\n    91|  If yes, it distills the solution into a Skill file saved to ~/.hermes/skills/\\n    92|  The Skill captures: task description, execution steps, pitfalls to watch for.\\n    93|  Example: after importing a CSV to a database, it might auto-create csv-to-database.md\\n    94|  recording common cleaning steps, your preferred db connection method, and validation rules.\\n    95|\\n    96|Step 3: Skill Self-Improvement\\n    97|  Every time a Skill is used and you provide feedback, Hermes modifies the Skill file itself.\\n    98|  You say \\\"this import script should check if the table exists first\\\" — Hermes doesn't just\\n    99|  add it this time, it edits the Skill file so the check is included by default next time.\\n   100|  Analogous to updating documentation + standards after a production incident.\\n   101|\\n   102|Step 4: FTS5 Cross-Session Recall\\n   103|  Before each new conversation, Hermes searches historical memory using FTS5 based on the\\n   104|  current topic and loads only the relevant fragments — not all history.\\n   105|  Ask a database question: loads database-related memories.\\n   106|  Ask a frontend question: loads frontend memories.\\n   107|  All data is local SQLite — never leaves your machine.\\n   108|\\n   109|Step 5: Honcho User Modeling (optional)\\n   110|  External integration by Plastic Labs. 12-layer dialectical identity modeling.\\n   111|  Infers user characteristics from behavior patterns, not just what you say.\\n   112|  Covers: technical level, work rhythm, communication style, goal inference, emotional\\n   113|  patterns, preference contradictions (what you say vs. what you actually do).\\n   114|  Results injected as invisible context into subsequent conversations.\\n   115|\\n   116|The causal chain (flywheel):\\n   117|  Memory feeds Skill creation → Skills generate new memories → new memories trigger Skill\\n   118|  improvement → improved Skills produce better results → better results make Honcho modeling\\n   119|  more accurate → more accurate profiling makes memory curation more targeted.\\n   120|\\n   121|Mitchell Hashimoto comparison: Mitchell manually added rules to CLAUDE.md every time Claude\\n   122|made a mistake. Hermes automates exactly this process. Trade-off: you give up some control\\n   123|over the rules, but the barrier drops to zero.\\n   124|\\n   125|### §04 — Three-Layer Memory: From Goldfish to Old Friend\\n   126|\\n   127|Each layer answers a different question. All stored locally in SQLite — no cloud dependency.\\n   128|All data lives in ~/.hermes/ — fully portable (copy directory to migrate machines).\\n   129|\\n   130|**Layer 1 — Session Memory (Episodic)**\\n   131|  Question: \\\"What happened?\\\"\\n   132|  - Every conversation, tool call, and return result written to SQLite with FTS5 indexing\\n   133|  - On-demand retrieval: NOT loading all history — searching relevant fragments per topic\\n   134|  - Analogy to hippocampus (episodic memory in cognitive science)\\n   135|\\n   136|  Approach         | Context Usage              | Long-term Viability | Speed\\n   137|  -----------------|----------------------------|---------------------|---------------------\\n   138|  Load Everything  | Grows linearly             | Hits wall after days| Gets slower over time\\n   139|  Hermes FTS5      | Essentially constant       | Works for months/years | Stays the same\\n   140|\\n   141|**Layer 2 — Persistent Memory (Semantic)**\\n   142|  Question: \\\"Who are you?\\\"\\n   143|  - Stores durable state: coding preferences, project structure habits, toolchain patterns\\n   144|  - Persists across sessions, survives new conversations — does not wipe on restart\\n   145|  - Also stored in SQLite, managed via the memory tool\\n   146|  - Portable: copy ~/.hermes/ to migrate; mount /opt/data in Docker for persistence\\n   147|  - Human can override, add, or delete entries at any time\\n   148|\\n   149|**Layer 3 — Skill Memory (Procedural)**\\n   150|  Question: \\\"How to do things?\\\"\\n   151|  - Each Skill is a standalone markdown file in ~/.hermes/skills/\\n   152|  - Human-readable and directly editable\\n   153|  - Records methodologies and operating procedures, not conversation content\\n   154|  - Auto-created by the agent, manually writable, or installed from the community Hub\\n   155|\\n   156|Cognitive science mapping:\\n   157|  - Session memory   = episodic memory  (\\\"what happened last time\\\")\\n   158|  - Persistent memory = semantic memory  (\\\"what the world is like\\\")\\n   159|  - Skill memory     = procedural memory (\\\"how to do things\\\")\\n   160|\\n   161|**Honcho: 12-Layer Dialectical User Modeling**\\n   162|\\n   163|After each conversation, Honcho infers:\\n   164|  - Technical level and skill\\n   165|  - Work rhythm and active hours\\n   166|  - Communication style preferences\\n   167|  - Goal inference from task patterns\\n   168|  - Emotional patterns (concise answers when frustrated)\\n   169|  - Preference contradictions (what you say vs. what you actually do)\\n   170|\\n   171|Key: Honcho catches inconsistencies between stated and revealed preferences. You never said\\n   172|\\\"I prefer concise code style\\\" but it inferred it from how you modify code across sessions.\\n   173|\\n   174|**Memory Comparison: Hermes vs Claude Code**\\n   175|\\n   176|  Dimension            | Claude Code                           | Hermes Agent\\n   177|  ---------------------|---------------------------------------|----------------------------------\\n   178|  Memory format        | CLAUDE.md + auto-memory text files    | SQLite + FTS5 + Skill files\\n   179|  Write method         | CLAUDE.md manual, auto-memory semi    | Fully automatic, human can override\\n   180|  Retrieval            | CLAUDE.md loaded in full at startup   | On-demand FTS5 full-text search\\n   181|  Memory granularity   | Project-level (one CLAUDE.md)         | Both global and project-level\\n   182|  User modeling        | None (user writes preferences)        | Honcho auto-infers user profile\\n   183|  Procedural memory    | Instructions in CLAUDE.md             | Standalone Skill files, self-improving\\n   184|  Storage limit        | CLAUDE.md recommended a few KB        | SQLite's theoretical limit is very high\\n   185|\\n   186|**Memory Limitations (important)**\\n   187|  - No automatic expiration: database grows with long-term use — audit ~/.hermes/ periodically\\n   188|  - Memory pollution: wrong early inferences persist and affect later behavior\\n   189|  - Only store preferences, habits, and patterns — not one-off tasks or sensitive info\\n   190|  - Sensitive info (passwords, keys, personal identity) must not enter the memory store\\n   191|\\n   192|### §05 — The Skill System: Capabilities That Evolve on Their Own\\n   193|\\n   194|**What a Skill Is**\\n   195|\\n   196|Each Skill is a standalone markdown file in ~/.hermes/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md\\n   197|It captures the agent's procedural memory for how to do something. Three sources:\\n   198|\\n   199|  Source          | Description                                              | Scale\\n   200|  ----------------|----------------------------------------------------------|------------------\\n   201|  Bundled Skills  | Pre-built capabilities shipped with install (MLOps,      | 40+\\n   202|                  | GitHub workflows, research)                              |\\n   203|  Agent-Created   | After completing complex tasks, auto-distilled solutions | Grows with usage\\n   204|  Skills Hub      | Community-contributed skill packs, one-click install     | Continuously growing\\n   205|\\n   206|Agent-created Skills are the \\\"killer feature.\\\" Same \\\"write code\\\" Skill, after three weeks with\\n   207|a Python developer vs. a Rust developer, evolves into two entirely different versions.\\n   208|\\n   209|**Skill Self-Improvement Mechanism**\\n   210|\\n   211|  1  Execute the Skill\\n   212|     Agent follows the steps recorded in the Skill to complete the task\\n   213|\\n   214|  2  Collect Feedback\\n   215|     User reactions (satisfied / unsatisfied / corrections) logged to session memory\\n   216|\\n   217|  3  Update the Skill\\n   218|     Agent analyzes feedback and automatically modifies relevant steps in the Skill file\\n   219|\\n   220|  4  Next Execution Uses the New Version\\n   221|     Improved Skill takes effect automatically in subsequent tasks\\n   222|\\n   223|Skills are alive — they run inside a learning loop, automatically optimizing based on real\\n   224|feedback. Every Skill update is visible as a diff in ~/.hermes/skills/ — not a black box.\\n   225|\\n   226|**agentskills.io Standard**\\n   227|\\n   228|Hermes Skills follow the agentskills.io standard, supported by 30+ tools as of early 2026\\n   229|including Claude Code, Cursor, Copilot, Codex CLI, and Gemini CLI. This means:\\n   230|  - Skills written for Claude Code work directly in Hermes\\n   231|  - Skills Hermes auto-creates can be used in Claude Code\\n   232|  - Your Skill library is a portable asset, not locked to any single tool\\n   233|  - OpenClaw's 5,700+ ClawHub Skills are callable via agentskills.io standard\\n   234|\\n   235|**Comparison: Hermes Skills vs OpenClaw Skills**\\n   236|\\n   237|  Dimension       | OpenClaw Skills                 | Hermes Skills\\n   238|  ----------------|---------------------------------|------------------------------------------\\n   239|  Creation        | Manually written SOUL.md        | Agent-created + manually written\\n   240|  Maintenance     | Manual updates                  | Auto-evolution + manual intervention\\n   241|  Personalization | Generic templates, fork/customize | Grows organically from your usage habits\\n   242|  Interoperability| agentskills.io standard         | agentskills.io standard (interoperable)\\n   243|  Ecosystem Size  | 5,700+ (large)                  | 40+ bundled + community (growing)\\n   244|\\n   245|OpenClaw strength: scale and transparency (you know exactly what every step does — you wrote it).\\n   246|Hermes strength: adaptability (grows into a custom fit from your actual usage patterns).\\n   247|\\n   248|### §06 — 40+ Tools and MCP: Connect Everything\\n   249|\\n   250|**Five Tool Categories**\\n   251|\\n   252|  Category     | Core Tools                     | What They Do\\n   253|  -------------|--------------------------------|------------------------------------------------\\n   254|  Execution    | terminal, code_execution, file | Run commands, execute code (sandboxed), read/write files\\n   255|  Information  | web, browser, session_search   | Web search, browser automation, search conversation history\\n   256|  Media        | vision, image_gen, tts         | Understand images, generate images, text-to-speech\\n   257|  Memory       | memory, skills, todo, cronjob  | Operate memory layer, manage Skills, task planning, scheduled jobs\\n   258|  Coordination | delegation, moa, clarify       | Delegate to sub-agents, multi-model reasoning, ask user\\n   259|\\n   260|Notable tools:\\n   261|  - session_search: FTS5 full-text search over conversation history with LLM summarization.\\n   262|    Most agents don't have this — every conversation starts from scratch.\\n   263|  - moa (Multi-model Orchestrated Answering): calls multiple LLMs simultaneously, synthesizes\\n   264|    into one answer. Useful for fact-checking or technical decisions requiring high reliability.\\n   265|  - cronjob: scheduled tasks in natural language. \\\"Check GitHub notifications every morning at\\n   266|    9am\\\" — no cron expressions, no scheduler config needed.\\n   267|\\n   268|**Toolsets: On-Demand, Not Everything On**\\n   269|\\n   270|Tools grouped into Toolsets and enabled/disabled in config.yaml:\\n   271|\\n   272|  toolsets:\\n   273|    - web\\n   274|    - terminal\\n   275|    - file\\n   276|    - skills\\n   277|    - delegation\\n   278|    # - homeassistant  # comment out what you don't need\\n   279|\\n   280|Fewer enabled tools = more focused agent + faster responses + fewer tokens consumed.\\n   281|Toolsets are also the constraint layer — precise control over what the agent can touch.\\n   282|\\n   283|**MCP: A Unified Interface to 6,000+ Apps**\\n   284|\\n   285|MCP (Model Context Protocol) — proposed by Anthropic, late 2024. The \\\"USB port\\\" of AI tools.\\n   286|Two transport modes:\\n   287|  - stdio: local subprocess, communicates over stdin/stdout. Fast, no network overhead.\\n   288|    Use for local tools, filesystems, databases.\\n   289|  - HTTP (StreamableHTTP): remote server, shared across multiple agents.\\n   290|    Use for cloud services or team-shared MCP servers.\\n   291|\\n   292|Per-server tool filtering: an MCP Server may expose 20 tools — restrict the agent to 3 of them.\\n   293|Common integrations: GitHub, Slack, Jira, Google Drive, databases, Notion, etc.\\n   294|\\n   295|---\\n   296|\\n   297|## Part 3: Hands-On Setup\\n   298|\\n   299|### §07 — Installation and Configuration: Three Approaches\\n   300|\\n   301|**Option 1: Local Install (5 minutes)**\\n   302|\\n   303|  curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/main/scripts/install.sh | bash\\n   304|  # Edit ~/.hermes/config.yaml with API key\\n   305|  hermes\\n   306|\\n   307|Works on macOS, Linux, WSL2. Handles Python, Node.js, and all dependencies automatically.\\n   308|Verify: hermes --version (should show v0.7.0)\\n   309|\\n   310|**Option 2: Docker (Clean Isolation)**\\n   311|\\n   312|  docker pull nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest\\n   313|  docker run -v ~/.hermes:/opt/data nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest\\n   314|\\n   315|Key: -v flag maps container data volume to host. All state (memory, Skills, config) in /opt/data.\\n   316|Delete and rebuild the container — your data survives.\\n   317|\\n   318|**Option 3: $5 VPS for 24/7 Uptime**\\n   319|\\n   320|  VPS Provider        | Monthly Cost | Notes\\n   321|  --------------------|--------------|----------------------------------\\n   322|  Hetzner CX22        | ~$4/mo       | Best value, European nodes\\n   323|  DigitalOcean Droplet| $5/mo        | Singapore/US West nodes\\n   324|  Vultr               | $5/mo        | Tokyo node, low latency\\n   325|\\n   326|Pick Ubuntu 22.04 LTS, SSH in, run the install script — identical to local installation.\\n   327|Without local LLMs, memory usage stays under 500MB. Pair with Telegram Gateway for\\n   328|phone access. Price of a coffee = 24-hour AI assistant.\\n   329|\\n   330|Serverless option: Daytona or Modal as backends. Hibernates when idle, wakes on message.\\n   331|Set terminal: daytona or terminal: modal in config.yaml.\\n   332|\\n   333|**config.yaml Deep Dive**\\n   334|\\n   335|Minimal working config:\\n   336|\\n   337|  model:\\n   338|    provider: openrouter\\n   339|    api_key: sk-or-xxxxx\\n   340|    model: anthropic/claude-sonnet-4\\n   341|  terminal: local\\n   342|  gateway:\\n   343|    telegram:\\n   344|      token: YOUR_BOT_TOKEN\\n   345|    discord:\\n   346|      token: YOUR_BOT_TOKEN\\n   347|\\n   348|Supported providers:\\n   349|\\n   350|  Provider     | Recommended Models          | Best For\\n   351|  -------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------\\n   352|  OpenRouter   | Claude Sonnet 4 / GPT-4o   | 200+ models, flexible switching\\n   353|  Nous Portal  | Hermes 3 series             | Officially recommended, deeply integrated\\n   354|  OpenAI       | GPT-4o / o3                 | Direct OpenAI API connection\\n   355|  z.ai / Zhipu | GLM-5                       | China-friendly option\\n   356|  Ollama       | Hermes 3 8B/70B             | Fully offline, privacy first\\n   357|\\n   358|Note (April 2026): Anthropic banned third-party tools from accessing Claude through Pro/Max\\n   359|subscriptions. Use Claude via pay-as-you-go API keys, or use OpenRouter / Nous Portal instead.\\n   360|\\n   361|Terminal backends (where code executes):\\n   362|  local, docker, ssh, daytona, modal, singularity\\n   363|  Recommendation: local for most users; docker if you want isolation on production servers.\\n   364|\\n   365|**Troubleshooting**\\n   366|  - Install script hanging: Check network / proxy for regions with restricted access\\n   367|  - hermes command not found: Run source ~/.bashrc or reopen terminal (fish shell quirk)\\n   368|  - Docker container starts but nothing happens: Ensure config.yaml exists and has model info\\n   369|\\n   370|### §08 — First Conversation: Letting Hermes Get to Know You\\n   371|\\n   372|After first launch, the ~/.hermes/ directory structure:\\n   373|\\n   374|  ~/.hermes/\\n   375|  ├── config.yaml           # Your configuration\\n   376|  ├── state.db              # SQLite database (conversation history + FTS5 index)\\n   377|  ├── skills/               # Skills directory\\n   378|  │   └── bundled/          # Built-in Skills\\n   379|  └── memories/             # Persistent memory (MEMORY.md + USER.md)\\n   380|\\n   381|What happens behind the scenes from your first message:\\n   382|  - Session memory is written to state.db immediately\\n   383|  - Preferences mentioned casually are saved to persistent memory layer\\n   384|  - After complex tasks, Hermes auto-creates a Skill file in skills/\\n   385|  - You don't write config, edit files, or set rules — just use it\\n   386|\\n   387|Skill auto-creation example: Ask Hermes to convert Markdown to WeChat-blog HTML. After\\n   388|completing it, check ~/.hermes/skills/ — a markdown-to-wechat.md Skill has appeared,\\n   389|recording the conversion rules and output requirements for future reuse.\\n   390|\\n   391|### §09 — Multi-Platform Access: Reach It Anywhere\\n   392|\\n   393|**Gateway Architecture: One Process, All Platforms**\\n   394|\\n   395|One Hermes Agent instance. One memory. One Skill set. All platforms.\\n   396|A message from Telegram and a command from the CLI are indistinguishable to Hermes.\\n   397|\\n   398|14 supported platforms: Telegram, Discord, Slack, WhatsApp, Signal, Email, SMS (Twilio),\\n   399|Home Assistant, Mattermost, Matrix, DingTalk, Feishu/Lark, WeCom, Open WebUI.\\n   400|\\n   401|**Telegram Bot Setup (Recommended Entry Point)**\\n   402|\\n   403|  1. Find @BotFather in Telegram → /newbot → get Token\\n   404|  2. Add to config.yaml:\\n   405|       gateway:\\n   406|         telegram:\\n   407|           token: 123456789:ABCdefGhIJKlmNoPQRsTUVwxyz\\n   408|  3. Run: hermes\\n   409|\\n   410|Three steps, under two minutes. Telegram also supports voice messages — auto-transcribed\\n   411|before processing. Say something during your commute; no typing needed.\\n   412|\\n   413|**Cross-Platform Conversation Continuity**\\n   414|\\n   415|Start a task on Telegram from your phone, continue it in the terminal at the office.\\n   416|No re-explaining context — one brain, all doors. What you said on Telegram can be\\n   417|continued in the CLI; Discord channel conversations can be referenced from Slack.\\n   418|\\n   419|**Automated Scheduling via Gateway**\\n   420|\\n   421|Scheduled task results get pushed through the Gateway to whatever platform you specify.\\n   422|Hermes doesn't just wait for you to talk — it can work proactively.\\n   423|Example: \\\"Send me a news briefing every morning at 8am\\\" → delivers to Telegram daily.\\n   424|\\n   425|**Practical Full Deployment Setup**\\n   426|\\n   427|  $5 VPS (Ubuntu 22.04)\\n   428|  ├── Hermes Agent Core\\n   429|  ├── Messaging Gateway\\n   430|  │   ├── Telegram Bot (reachable from phone)\\n   431|  │   ├── Discord Bot (team collaboration)\\n   432|  │   └── Slack App (enterprise use)\\n   433|  ├── ~/.hermes/\\n   434|  │   ├── state.db (all conversation history)\\n   435|  │   ├── skills/ (capabilities that accumulate automatically)\\n   436|  │   └── config.yaml (one file, everything configured)\\n   437|  └── Model calls → OpenRouter API\\n   438|\\n   439|Total cost: VPS $5/month + model API fees ($2-5/month for light usage).\\n   440|\\n   441|### §10 — Custom Skills: Teaching Hermes New Tricks\\n   442|\\n   443|**Skill File Format and Structure**\\n   444|\\n   445|A Skill is a markdown file. No framework to learn, no API to call.\\n   446|Each Skill lives in its own folder under ~/.hermes/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md\\n   447|Optional subdirectories: references/, templates/, scripts/\\n   448|\\n   449|YAML frontmatter:\\n   450|\\n   451|  ---\\n   452|  name: skill-name\\n   453|  description: What this Skill does\\n   454|  version: \\\"1.0.0\\\"\\n   455|  ---\\n   456|\\n   457|Complete Skill anatomy (from the book's git-commit-style example):\\n   458|\\n   459|  ---\\n   460|  name: git-commit-style\\n   461|  description: Enforce a consistent Git commit message format\\n   462|  version: \\\"1.0.0\\\"\\n   463|  ---\\n   464|  # Git Commit Style\\n   465|\\n   466|  ## Trigger\\n   467|  Activate when the user asks me to commit code, write a commit message, or review commit history.\\n   468|\\n   469|  ## Rules\\n   470|  ### Commit Message Format\\n   471|  - First line: type(scope): summary (50 chars max)\\n   472|  - Blank line\\n   473|  - Body: explain WHY, not WHAT\\n   474|\\n   475|  ### Type Enum\\n   476|  - feat: new feature\\n   477|  - fix: bug fix\\n   478|  - refactor: restructure (no behavior change)\\n   479|  - docs: documentation\\n   480|  - test: tests\\n   481|  - chore: build/toolchain\\n   482|\\n   483|  ### Constraints\\n   484|  - Body in plain language, types in English\\n   485|  - Don't write \\\"modified XX file\\\" -- that's noise\\n   486|  - One commit, one thing\\n   487|\\n   488|  ## Example\\n   489|  feat(auth): add WeChat QR code login\\n   490|  (reason for change)\\n   491|\\n   492|**Anatomy of a Good Skill (from the book's empirical analysis)**\\n   493|\\n   494|  Section   | Purpose                             | Required?\\n   495|  ----------|-------------------------------------|-------------------\\n   496|  Title     | Lets Hermes quickly identify what   | Yes\\n   497|            | the Skill does                      |\\n   498|  Trigger   | When to activate this Skill         | Strongly recommended\\n   499|  Rules     | Concrete steps, constraints, formats| Yes\\n   500|  Example   | A complete input-to-output example  | Strongly recommended\\n   501|\", \"total_lines\": 1005, \"file_size\": 48361, \"truncated\": true, \"hint\": \"Use offset=501 to continue reading (showing 1-500 of 1005 lines)\", \"is_binary\": false, \"is_image\": false}", "tool_call_id": "tool_read_file_0QxekDIDZXPWxHIiuMNk", "tool_calls": null, "tool_name": null, "timestamp": 1777106882.2744832, "token_count": null, "finish_reason": null, "reasoning": null, "reasoning_details": null, "codex_reasoning_items": null}, {"id": 586, "session_id": "20260425_082424_dec2c3ed", "role": "assistant", "content": "", "tool_call_id": null, "tool_calls": [{"id": "tool_read_file_nTBooE1sBKcW43aS4bnM", "call_id": "tool_read_file_nTBooE1sBKcW43aS4bnM", "response_item_id": "fc_tool_read_file_nTBooE1sBKcW43aS4bnM", "type": "function", "function": {"name": "read_file", "arguments": "{\"path\":\"/root/workspace/my-wiki/wiki/cognee-setup.md\"}"}}], "tool_name": null, "timestamp": 1777106882.2785175, "token_count": null, "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "reasoning": null, "reasoning_details": null, "codex_reasoning_items": null}, {"id": 587, "session_id": "20260425_082424_dec2c3ed", "role": "tool", "content": "{\"content\": \"     1|---\\n     2|title: Cognee — Memory Layer Setup for DVS Agent Swarm\\n     3|created: 2026-04-23\\n     4|updated: 2026-04-23\\n     5|type: concept\\n     6|tags: [memory, knowledge-graph, infrastructure, agents, tool]\\n     7|sources: [https://github.com/topoteretes/cognee]\\n     8|---\\n     9|\\n    10|# Cognee — Memory Layer Setup for DVS Agent Swarm\\n    11|\\n    12|Cognee is an open-source knowledge engine that replaces flat markdown retrieval with a\\n    13|persistent, graph-backed memory layer. It combines vector search, graph databases, and\\n    14|cognitive science principles so that ingested documents are both searchable by meaning\\n    15|and connected by relationships.\\n    16|\\n    17|For DVS, Cognee becomes Athena's primary retrieval backend — the wiki markdown files\\n    18|remain as the human-readable, version-controlled source of truth, but Cognee indexes\\n    19|their content into a knowledge graph for fast, relationship-aware query routing.\\n    20|\\n    21|Related: [[agent-build-order.md]] [[hermes-orange-book.md]] [[CONTEXT.md]]\\n    22|\\n    23|---\\n    24|\\n    25|## 1. Installation\\n    26|\\n    27|Cognee is installed on Zo (Hermes host machine) via pip.\\n    28|\\n    29|Status as of 2026-04-23: INSTALLED\\n    30|\\n    31|```\\n    32|pip install cognee\\n    33|```\\n    34|\\n    35|Python requirement: 3.10 to 3.13\\n    36|Key dependencies installed: lancedb, sqlalchemy, openai, tiktoken, neo4j client,\\n    37|networkx, fastapi, uvicorn, pydantic\\n    38|\\n    39|Verify:\\n    40|```\\n    41|python -c \\\"import cognee; print(cognee.__version__)\\\"\\n    42|```\\n    43|\\n    44|---\\n    45|\\n    46|## 2. Configuration\\n    47|\\n    48|Cognee requires an LLM API key at minimum. Set it in the environment or a .env file.\\n    49|\\n    50|```bash\\n    51|export LLM_API_KEY=\\\"your-o...-key\\\"\\n    52|```\\n    53|\\n    54|Or in ~/.hermes/.env (recommended for Hermes integration):\\n    55|```\\n    56|LLM_API_KEY=your-o...-key\\n    57|```\\n    58|\\n    59|To switch LLM providers (Anthropic, Mistral, local Ollama, etc.) see:\\n    60|https://docs.cognee.ai/\\n    61|\\n    62|For Cognee Cloud (managed, no local DB required):\\n    63|```python\\n    64|import cognee\\n    65|await cognee.serve(url=\\\"https://your-instance.cognee.ai\\\", api_key=\\\"ck_...\\\")\\n    66|```\\n    67|\\n    68|Default local storage: SQLite + LanceDB (zero-config, good for DVS dev phase).\\n    69|Production upgrade path: PostgreSQL + Qdrant or Neo4j.\\n    70|\\n    71|---\\n    72|\\n    73|## 3. The Four Core API Calls\\n    74|\\n    75|Cognee exposes four operations. All are async.\\n    76|\\n    77|### remember(data, dataset=None, session_id=None)\\n    78|\\n    79|Ingests data permanently into the knowledge graph.\\n    80|Runs the full pipeline: chunk -> embed -> extract entities -> build graph relations.\\n    81|\\n    82|```python\\n    83|import cognee\\n    84|import asyncio\\n    85|\\n    86|await cognee.remember(\\\"Athena is the wiki and research agent of the DVS swarm.\\\")\\n    87|await cognee.remember(\\\"ETHis 2026 takes place at Deutsches Museum Munich, July 2-3.\\\")\\n    88|\\n    89|# With a session scope (fast cache, syncs to graph in background):\\n    90|await cognee.remember(\\\"User prefers concise answers.\\\", session_id=\\\"chat_1\\\")\\n    91|```\\n    92|\\n    93|Use this for:\\n    94|- Onboarding all wiki pages at init time\\n    95|- Adding new knowledge after Athena ingests a source\\n    96|- Capturing agent decisions and outputs for cross-agent memory\\n    97|\\n    98|### recall(query, dataset=None, session_id=None)\\n    99|\\n   100|Queries the knowledge graph with auto-routing — Cognee picks the best search\\n   101|strategy (vector similarity, graph traversal, or hybrid) based on the query type.\\n   102|\\n   103|```python\\n   104|results = await cognee.recall(\\\"What is the DVS build order?\\\")\\n   105|for r in results:\\n   106|    print(r)\\n   107|\\n   108|# Session-scoped recall (checks session memory first, falls through to graph):\\n   109|results = await cognee.recall(\\\"What did we discuss today?\\\", session_id=\\\"chat_1\\\")\\n   110|```\\n   111|\\n   112|Use this as the primary retrieval call. Replaces grep-based search of markdown files.\\n   113|\\n   114|### forget(dataset=None)\\n   115|\\n   116|Deletes a dataset from the knowledge graph. Use carefully.\\n   117|\\n   118|```python\\n   119|await cognee.forget(dataset=\\\"staging_test\\\")\\n   120|```\\n   121|\\n   122|For Athena: use to remove stale ingestions when a wiki page is archived or superseded.\\n   123|Never call forget() on the main dataset without Donny's explicit approval.\\n   124|\\n   125|### improve(data)\\n   126|\\n   127|Feeds corrective feedback into the graph — updates existing nodes, resolves\\n   128|contradictions, reinforces correct relationships.\\n   129|\\n   130|```python\\n   131|await cognee.improve(\\\"ETHis 2026 is organized by DVS in partnership with Ethereum Foundation.\\\")\\n   132|```\\n   133|\\n   134|Use this after Donny corrects Athena's output. The correction becomes persistent.\\n   135|Maps directly to the wiki's Update Policy for contradiction handling.\\n   136|\\n   137|---\\n   138|\\n   139|## 4. CLI Interface\\n   140|\\n   141|Cognee ships a CLI for quick ops without writing Python:\\n   142|\\n   143|```bash\\n   144|cognee-cli remember \\\"Cognee is the memory layer for DVS agents.\\\"\\n   145|cognee-cli recall \\\"What is DVS?\\\"\\n   146|cognee-cli forget --all\\n   147|cognee-cli -ui    # opens local browser UI at localhost\\n   148|```\\n   149|\\n   150|The -ui flag launches a local dashboard for browsing the knowledge graph visually.\\n   151|Useful for debugging ingestion and inspecting entity relationships.\\n   152|\\n   153|---\\n   154|\\n   155|## 5. Athena Integration Plan — Replacing Flat Markdown Retrieval\\n   156|\\n   157|### Current State (Flat Markdown)\\n   158|\\n   159|Athena currently retrieves knowledge by:\\n   160|1. Reading index.md to find relevant page names\\n   161|2. Calling read_file on those pages\\n   162|3. Calling search_files with regex patterns across the wiki directory\\n   163|\\n   164|Limitations:\\n   165|- No semantic search — misses synonyms, conceptual matches\\n   166|- No relationship traversal — cannot follow entity links automatically\\n   167|- Retrieval quality degrades as wiki grows past ~50 pages\\n   168|- Each session re-scans from scratch — no compounding query cache\\n   169|\\n   170|### Target State (Cognee-backed)\\n   171|\\n   172|Athena ingests all wiki pages into Cognee at session start (or delta-syncs changed\\n   173|pages). Queries route through cognee.recall() first. Markdown files remain the\\n   174|authoritative write surface — Cognee is the read index.\\n   175|\\n   176|### Migration Steps\\n   177|\\n   178|Step 1: Bootstrap ingest (one-time)\\n   179|  - Read all files from wiki/ directory\\n   180|  - Call cognee.remember() for each page with the dataset=\\\"dvs_wiki\\\" tag\\n   181|  - Verify recall works: cognee.recall(\\\"DVS agent build order\\\")\\n   182|\\n   183|Step 2: Delta sync on ingest\\n   184|  - After Athena writes or updates any wiki page, immediately call cognee.remember()\\n   185|    with the updated content\\n   186|  - Use dataset=\\\"dvs_wiki\\\" consistently so recall searches the full wiki corpus\\n   187|\\n   188|Step 3: Replace search_files with recall for queries\\n   189|  - Before: search_files(\\\"ethereum\\\", path=wiki, file_glob=\\\"*.md\\\")\\n   190|  - After: cognee.recall(\\\"ethereum projects in DVS\\\")\\n   191|  - Fall back to search_files only if Cognee returns empty results (safety net)\\n   192|\\n   193|Step 4: Use improve() for corrections\\n   194|  - When Donny corrects a fact, call both:\\n   195|    a. patch() to update the markdown file (human-readable truth)\\n   196|    b. cognee.improve() with the corrected statement (graph truth)\\n   197|\\n   198|Step 5: Session memory for agent coordination\\n   199|  - Each agent uses session_id = agent name + date\\n   200|  - cognee.remember(decision, session_id=\\\"athena-2026-04-23\\\")\\n   201|  - Other agents can recall Athena's session context without reading full wiki\\n   202|\\n   203|### Bootstrap Script\\n   204|\\n   205|```python\\n   206|import cognee\\n   207|import asyncio\\n   208|import os\\n   209|\\n   210|WIKI_PATH = \\\"/root/workspace/my-wiki/wiki\\\"\\n   211|DATASET = \\\"dvs_wiki\\\"\\n   212|\\n   213|async def bootstrap_wiki():\\n   214|    for fname in os.listdir(WIKI_PATH):\\n   215|        if not fname.endswith(\\\".md\\\"):\\n   216|            continue\\n   217|        fpath = os.path.join(WIKI_PATH, fname)\\n   218|        with open(fpath, \\\"r\\\") as f:\\n   219|            content = f.read()\\n   220|        print(f\\\"Ingesting {fname}...\\\")\\n   221|        await cognee.remember(content, dataset=DATASET)\\n   222|        print(f\\\"  done.\\\")\\n   223|\\n   224|    # Verify\\n   225|    results = await cognee.recall(\\\"DVS agent swarm\\\", dataset=DATASET)\\n   226|    print(f\\\"Recall test returned {len(results)} results.\\\")\\n   227|    for r in results:\\n   228|        print(\\\" -\\\", r)\\n   229|\\n   230|asyncio.run(bootstrap_wiki())\\n   231|```\\n   232|\\n   233|Run this once: python /root/workspace/my-wiki/scripts/bootstrap_cognee.py\\n   234|\\n   235|---\\n   236|\\n   237|## 6. Hermes Native Integration\\n   238|\\n   239|Cognee is a first-class provider in Hermes Agent's memory system.\\n   240|To activate (in ~/.hermes/config.yaml):\\n   241|\\n   242|```yaml\\n   243|memory:\\n   244|  provider: cognee\\n   245|```\\n   246|\\n   247|Then set LLM_API_KEY in ~/.hermes/.env and restart Hermes.\\n   248|Session memory and graph persistence become automatic — no manual API calls needed.\\n   249|All agents in the swarm that run under Hermes inherit Cognee memory automatically.\\n   250|\\n   251|---\\n   252|\\n   253|## 7. MCP Integration\\n   254|\\n   255|Cognee ships an MCP server (cognee-mcp/) for direct tool access by any MCP-capable agent.\\n   256|See the native-mcp skill for how to configure MCP servers in Hermes.\\n   257|\\n   258|Potential: expose cognee remember/recall as native Hermes tools so all swarm agents\\n   259|can write and read shared memory without direct Python SDK calls.\\n   260|\\n   261|---\\n   262|\\n   263|## 8. Architecture Context\\n   264|\\n   265|Cognee under the hood (local dev mode):\\n   266|- Vector store: LanceDB (local columnar, no server required)\\n   267|- Graph store: SQLite-backed NetworkX (upgradeable to Neo4j)\\n   268|- Embeddings: OpenAI text-embedding-3-small by default\\n   269|- Entity extraction: LLM-driven NER pass during cognify step\\n   270|- Chunking: automatic, respects document structure\\n   271|\\n   272|This means every cognee.remember() call:\\n   273|1. Chunks the text\\n   274|2. Embeds each chunk\\n   275|3. Stores vectors in LanceDB\\n   276|4. Extracts named entities and relationships via LLM\\n   277|5. Writes nodes + edges into the graph store\\n   278|\\n   279|Every cognee.recall() call:\\n   280|1. Embeds the query\\n   281|2. Runs vector ANN search (fast path)\\n   282|3. Optionally traverses graph neighbors for richer context\\n   283|4. Returns ranked results\\n   284|\\n   285|---\\n   286|\\n   287|## 9. Open Questions / Next Steps\\n   288|\\n   289|- [ ] Confirm LLM_API_KEY is set in Zo's environment before running bootstrap\\n   290|- [ ] Decide: local SQLite+LanceDB vs PostgreSQL+Qdrant for production DVS\\n   291|- [ ] Evaluate: Cognee Cloud (managed) vs self-hosted for swarm scale\\n   292|- [ ] Test recall quality on existing wiki pages (6 pages, good benchmark set)\\n   293|- [ ] Wire delta-sync into Athena's ingest workflow (Step 2 above)\\n   294|- [ ] Explore cognee-mcp for tool-level access by non-Python agents in swarm\\n   295|- [ ] Consider: use Cognee session memory for CONTEXT.md handoff (replace flat file)\\n   296|\\n   297|---\\n   298|\\n   299|## References\\n   300|\\n   301|- GitHub: https://github.com/topoteretes/cognee\\n   302|- Docs: https://docs.cognee.ai/\\n   303|- Research paper: arxiv.org/abs/2505.24478 (Optimizing KG Interface for LLM Reasoning)\\n   304|- Colab walkthrough: linked in repo README\\n   305|- MCP server: cognee-mcp/ directory in repo\\n   306|- Hermes integration: README section \\\"Use with AI Agents > Hermes Agent\\\"\\n   307|\", \"total_lines\": 306, \"file_size\": 9657, \"truncated\": false, \"is_binary\": false, \"is_image\": false}", "tool_call_id": "tool_read_file_nTBooE1sBKcW43aS4bnM", "tool_calls": null, "tool_name": null, "timestamp": 1777106882.2787213, "token_count": null, "finish_reason": null, "reasoning": null, "reasoning_details": null, "codex_reasoning_items": null}, {"id": 588, "session_id": "20260425_082424_dec2c3ed", "role": "assistant", "content": "", "tool_call_id": null, "tool_calls": [{"id": "tool_read_file_EqymYDEukJyKK5FgDLzg", "call_id": "tool_read_file_EqymYDEukJyKK5FgDLzg", "response_item_id": "fc_tool_read_file_EqymYDEukJyKK5FgDLzg", "type": "function", "function": {"name": "read_file", "arguments": "{\"path\":\"/root/workspace/my-wiki/wiki/CONTEXT.md\"}"}}], "tool_name": null, "timestamp": 1777106882.2795815, 