hilst I call it heart, you may call it gut. Some others may call it conscience like Pinocchio’s Jiminy Cricket. Others still might state that it’s your soul’s voice, or even your higher self.\n\nHowever you choose to address it, it can be irritatingly accurate, the more strength you give it. But like any muscle, it needs to be exercised. Every relationship needs to be given the opportunity to build trust, and the more you extend that trust, the stronger it gets and the better it will serve you. \n\nReally, the whole concept of trusting your heart is achingly simple. It’s merely about listening to her.\n\nShe is the one who tells us when we are with the wrong person or when another is being mean to us. She is the voice that tells us that we deserve better, or are not being treated fairly. But listening can prove to be very difficult. We have found a myriad of ways to avoid her loving ramblings, be it through alcohol, drugs, social media, work, mindless Netflix series, or even just plain ignoring her.\n\nIf we are brave enough to head her advice, there are times, when she will get through to you at such a cosmically perfect moment, that will ever so slightly alter your trajectory, towards a better destination.\n\nUpgrade to paid\n\n…………………………….\n\nIt was 2008 and I was five years into building my photography career. My agent called me as I walked through Washington Square Park in New York, telling me that I had been asked by a supermodel of the time, to photograph her for the Blackglama campaign, a well-known fur company for which stars like Elizabeth Taylor, Pavarotti and Diana Ross, had all modeled, dripping head to toe, in mink.\n\nThis potential job was the first time I was faced with the fact that I wasn’t going to be photographing a few random pieces of fur amongst other clothes. It was going to be all fur and I would be paid incredibly well for it; more than I had ever been paid for anything else. But, as I opened my mouth to agree wholeheartedly to the handsome paycheck, my heart whispered two words to me:  Blood Money. \n\nOn one hand I was still at the beginning of my career,  I had many debts to pay, rent and utilities; not to mention a serious drinking habit to keep moist. On the other hand, a clear choice was being forced on to me. How could I remain indifferent and feign ignorance about how fur was produced, after being physically repulsed at the sight of animals being skinned, caged from birth, and self-mutilating as they went mad in their cells.\n\nAlexi, said my agent, interrupting my thoughts. This is a lot money and you are always asking me to get you money jobs. Here is one. \n\nAs the dollar signs dangled in front of me, trying to divert my attention with their bejazzled beauty, my heart kept butting in. At first it was a whisper; then a little bit louder; until frustrated, she rammed her hand up my throat, as if I were a ventriloquist dummy, and moved my mouth for me. I’m really sorry, I just don’t think I can do it, I blurted out.\n\nYou know that everyone photographs fur, right? answered my agent. You have already shot a lot of fur in editorials, so it doesn’t make much sense you turning this down now.\n\nMy brain was slapping its forehead. Are you crazy?! The money, Alexi! You are going to regret it, you dummkopf! You will be calling him right back, begging him for that job!\n\nOk Alexi, my agent surrendered. If that’s your final decision, I will let them know.\n\nI put the Blackberry in my pocket and stood under the Washington Square Arch.\n\nInstead of calling him right back and begging for the job, and that much needed money, something unexpected happened. My shoulders relaxed, I took a deep breath and felt a stillness that hadn’t been there before.\n\nIn that brief moment of quiet, my heart patted me on the back, put her head on my shoulder, and whispered in my ear, that I had made a very difficult decision, but for a very good reason. She told me that if clients trusted me enough to inspire people to buy their products through my creativity, then maybe I could make a positive difference by choosing not to do it. If I had the courage moving forward, how could I push that further still?\n\nUpgrade to paid\n\n…………………………….\n\nFast forward to 2019. After photographing Prince Harry and Megan Markle for their engagement and wedding pictures, my visibility went through the roof, and I immediately searched for a way to use that newfound notoriety, to try and inspire some sort of change within the fashion industry; to leave the industry in a better place than when I had entered it.\n\nAnd so, I started Creatives4Change, a movement born from the idea that each of us creatives who works in the fashion industry, holds incredible power to inspire, with every creative choice that we make, with the potential to send out either positive or negative ripples into the world.\n\nThe first initiative for the C4C project, was to ask creatives to sign a pledge that they would no longer use FUR, FEATHERS OR EXOTIC SKINS.\n\nUsing the fact that my name was currently being ping-ponged around the internet, within the Harry and Meghan news frenzy, I was able to wrangle meetings with industry leaders, who before, may have never even opened an email from me.\n\nI left the reason for our rendezvous somewhat ambiguous. Upon meeting, I would always begin by talking about how they got started, and what they thought about the industry. I would then wait for an opportune moment, lean in, smiling apologetically and gently ask them to sign the pledge, that they would no longer use fur, feathers, or exotic skins in their creative output. \n\nMany people’s eyes twitched, as they tried to hide their discomfort at having to address this question face to face. Some signed easily. Others didn’t. Others still, told me that, even though their hearts begged them to sign, the voice of fear, that spoke of losing clients and jobs, was louder. As a fellow freelancer, I was in no position to judge them for this concern. Everyone has their own journey, and I had to respect each person’s decision.\n\nI was not only targeting photographers, stylists, and magazines, but also fashion designers. One designer in particular, who was on my list was the legendary Diane von Furstenberg, but I was having no luck getting a meeting with her.\n\nThen one particularly warm NYC morning, as I returned home from dropping my sons off at school, I received a phone call.\n\nHello, this is the office of Diane Von Furstenberg. She can see you for 5 minutes; in 15 minutes.\n\nI’ll be there, I said before hanging up, putting on my least wrinkled shirt, grabbing a fresh C4C pledge document, and jumping on my bike, riding through every red light to get across town.\n\nOn arrival, at the DVF office in the meatpacking district, I was ushered into her office by an assistant. She was on the phone, and motioned for me to sit down in front of her desk. After a few Hmm Hmm’s and one Ok fine, she put her phone on the table, picked up a small camera and pointed it at me.\n\nClick. Click.\n\nYou’re very handsome, she said with a mischievous smile. \n\nI blushed, chuckled and mumbled in classic Hugh Grant fashion, Ah, well, I, uh, um, ah, before she interrupted me.\n\nI have five minutes. What can I do for you?\n\nI immediately started with my usual, quick fire facts about the negative side of fur, feathers and exotic skins in fashion, the cruelty and the environmental impact.\n\nAgain, she stopped me midsentence. Isn’t it funny how clothes can relate to one’s circumstances?\n\nOh? I responded.\n\nMy relatives were in concentration camps during the war, she began. And when they were released, they bought a heavy fur coat, with the reparation money they received, because they never wanted to feel the cold that they had felt in those camps in such horrific conditions.\n\nI cannot argue with that, I said. I cannot imagine what your relatives went through, and I think…\n\nI have one more minute, she interjected again, picking up a pen and writing something un-related onto a Post-it note, before sticking it next to five others on her desk.\n\nMy thoughts went into emergency mode, How would I convince her in one minute, without quoting more facts and figures? What was the key to Diane Von Furstenberg?\n\nSuddenly, I just started talking.\n\nDiane, you are a creative genius. Over the last forty odd years, you have proven yourself to be as such. No mathematical formula could predict that this particular pattern, with this particular design and color, would sell, but everything you have created has been a success, because YOU HAVE ALWAYS TRUSTED YOUR HEART.\n\nNow that you have the knowledge of how fur, feathers and exotic skins are produced, and the pain they inflict, WHAT DOES YOUR HEART TELL YOU IS THE RIGHT THING TO DO?\n\nShe looked at me, tapping her pen on the desk, with a twinkle in her eye.\n\nThat is very beautiful, she said. I sign.\n\nReally?! I spluttered, immediately wishing I seemed less surprised.\n\nI fumbled the C4C pledge out of my bag, onto the table and she signed right there and then.\n\nThe key to DVF was heart; the same key that we should all use, to unlock our life’s answers.\n\nAfter that, we obtained signed pledges from a wide array of creatives, including such people as Tonne Goodman of US Vogue, Laura Brown and IN STYLE magazine, Phillip Lim, Jennifer Aniston, Kate Winslet, photographers Inez & Vinoodh, to name just a few. Working in conjunction with PJ Smith and The Humane Society, we also got all 47 International ELLE magazine editions to sign a NO FUR pledge.\n\nUpgrade to paid\n\n………………..\n\nNow, apart from inspiring us to follow our authentic life force intentions, our hearts regularly revel in their ability to notify us when we have done something to hurt someone else, or even ourselves. \n\nWe try not to listen, attempting to avoid that heaviness in our belly; due to the knowing that underneath it all, our heart knows us better than anyone. They know who we really are inside, and more importantly, who we have the potential to be. No matter how far we drift off course, like a prodigal son, our heart will always welcome us back with open atriums.\n\nWe regularly hide our hearts from things that we know they will speak up about. We choose to avert our eyes from environmental issues, or human injustices and suffering, because we know that, as soon as our heart sees those images, it will cry out for us to help.\n\nThis help however, is halted two floors up, in the logical brain department, where change and the disruption of our organized life is frowned upon; but if we do allow our heart to witness the plight of others, she will not call on us simply to upset our world. She is telling us to step up to the plate and lend a helping hand, because our heart is connected to the one love that joins us all. It knows that by helping others, we are helping ourselves, because we are all one.\n\nHowever, this explanation does not make that pesky heart any less bothersome, when she tells us to do the very opposite of something that we have already meticulously planned to do.\n\nNobody likes being told that they are doing something wrong or driving in the wrong direction for hundreds of miles. In short, no one likes a backseat driver, and yet there we find our hearts, sat comfortably buckled up, behind our driver’s seat, with an irritating running commentary, on our words, actions and deeds.\n\nBut listen to our hearts, we must, because our spiritual survival and evolution depends on it. \n\nSo lend her your ear, take her hand, and allow her to lead you, to where you were always meant to go.\n\n \n\n“Listen to your heart. It knows all things, because it came from the Soul of the World and it will one day return there.” - Paolo Coelho. THE ALCHEMIST\n\n…………………………………..\n\nThe newsletter is free, but if you enjoy what I’m writing and want to donate, then all my proceeds from this page will be passed on to the humanitarian charity, CONCERN WORLDWIDE, of which I am an ambassador. Thank you for being here :-)\n\nYou're currently a free subscriber to LETTERS FROM A HUMAN BEING by Alexi Lubomirski. For the full experience, upgrade your subscription.\n\nUpgrade to paid\n LikeCommentRestack \n© 2023 ALEXI LUBOMIRSKI\n548 Market Street PMB 72296, San Francisco, CA 94104 \nUnsubscribe", "tool_call_id": null, "tool_calls": null, "tool_name": null, "timestamp": 1776813131.9995813, "token_count": null, "finish_reason": null, "reasoning": null, "reasoning_details": null, "codex_reasoning_items": null}, {"id": 2, "session_id": "20260421_231205_cb50d001", "role": "user", "content": "[Subject: payment structure]\n\n### **Payment Structure for Donny Lewis' Consulting Work**\r\nWhen structuring a payment plan based on an hourly rate of $275 for Donny Lewis' consulting work, it's essential to establish a clear and transparent framework that outlines the scope of work, deliverables, and payment terms. Below is a suggested structure:\r\n---\r\n### **1. Initial Consultation & Project Scoping**- **Purpose**: To define the project scope, objectives, and deliverables.- **Time Estimate**: 4-6 hours- **Cost Estimate**: $1,100 - $1,650- **Deliverables**:  - Detailed project plan and timeline.  - Initial assessment of the Sandbox's current eco-initiatives and potential areas for integration.  - Identification of key stakeholders and partners to involve.\r\n### **2. Partnership Development & Networking**- **Purpose**: To leverage Donny's network to onboard eco-friendly projects and establish strategic partnerships.- **Time Estimate**: 20-40 hours (dependent on the number of partnerships and the complexity of negotiations)- **Cost Estimate**: $5,500 - $11,000- **Deliverables**:  - Partnership agreements with green tech ReFi projects, DAO initiatives, and other eco-crypto projects.  - A pipeline of potential partners and collaboration opportunities.  - Regular updates and reports on partnership progress.\r\n### **3. Cu